I was thinking about a use-case like this:
ServiceFactory.Builder builder = new ServiceFactory.Builder();
builder.testBlocking(noOffloadsStrategy(), serviceImpl);
try {
    builder.testBlocking(anotherStrategy, anotherServiceImpl);
} catch (IllegalStateException e) {
    // ignore that this route was already registered
}
Don't think we need to verify duplication for the executionStrategies map, because we already do that for routes. An additional check will be useless.
In my first impl I stored execution strategy before I verified routes duplication. That's why in the example above users will be in the state when they have serviceImpl with anotherStrategy.
Now I moved executionStrategies.put(...) after we verify routes duplication. So, nothing will corrupt the internal state.

AFAIR, this is required only for disallowing filters to specify the strategy annotation, rite? I have not thought of that case as to whether it is good or bad.

Right. As we discussed before, ST policy is that if you configure an execution strategy for the route, ST will use it regardless of filters/influencers/etc.
The case here is that grpc filter implements the same service interface. Therefore, users can accidentally add @RouteExecutionStrategy annotation on the filter. I think we should ignore it.

so if we need special code to disallow it, lets refrain from doing that for now and have "behavior when strategy annotation is defined on filters is undefined" as our answer.

The code to disallow annotation inspection for filters is trivial. It's just getOrDefault vs get on the map to distinguish key-null entry vs entry for this key does not exist.
Defined behavior is always better than undefined. I've added this test to demonstrate the problem: https://github.com/apple/servicetalk/pull/932/files#diff-4fbfd0eed0161987f94f03bc6d9e3203R262-R279

